04485nam a22007215i 9780812290394DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013951885  a97808122903947 a10.9783/97808122903942doi  a(DE-B1597)456678  a(OCoLC)979904972  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR2807 -- .L385 2015eb 7aLIT0150002bisacsh04a822.3/3  aHI 3423qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/50026:1 aLesser, Zachary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut11a"Hamlet" After Q1 :bAn Uncanny History of the Shakespearean Text /cZachary Lesser. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b27 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMaterial Texts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. The Urn-Hamlet -- tChapter 1. As Originally Written by Shakespeare -- tChapter 2. Contrary Matters -- tChapter 3. Enter the Ghost in His Night Gowne -- tChapter 4. Conscience Makes Cowards -- tConclusion. Q1 in the Library at Babel -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1823, Sir Henry Bunbury discovered a badly bound volume of twelve Shakespeare plays in a closet of his manor house. Nearly all of the plays were first editions, but one stood out as extraordinary: a previously unknown text of Hamlet that predated all other versions. Suddenly, the world had to grapple with a radically new—or rather, old—Hamlet in which the characters, plot, and poetry of Shakespeare's most famous play were profoundly and strangely transformed.Q1, as the text is known, has been declared a rough draft, a shorthand piracy, a memorial reconstruction, and a pre-Shakespearean "ur-Hamlet," among other things. Flickering between two historical moments—its publication in Shakespeare's early seventeenth century and its rediscovery in Bunbury's early nineteenth—Q1 is both the first and last Hamlet. Because this text became widely known only after the familiar version of the play had reached the pinnacle of English literature, its reception has entirely depended on this uncanny temporal oscillation; so too has its ongoing influence on twentieth- and twenty-first-century ideas of the play.Zachary Lesser examines how the improbable discovery of Q1 has forced readers to reconsider accepted truths about Shakespeare as an author and about the nature of Shakespeare's texts. In telling the story of this mysterious quarto and tracing the debates in newspapers, London theaters, and scholarly journals that followed its discovery, Lesser offers brilliant new insights on what we think we mean when we talk about Hamlet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTransmission of textszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229039440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812290394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812290394.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK